r. Yet much is still unknown about the significance of the slavery business and emancipation in the formation of modern imperial Britain. This book engages with current work exploring the importance of slavery and slave-ownership in the re-making of the British imperial world after abolition in 1833.The contributors to this collection, drawn from Britain, the Caribbean and Mauritius, include some of the most distinguished writers in the field: Clare Anderson, Robin Blackburn, Heather Cateau, Mary Chamberlain, Chris Evans, Pat Hudson, Richard Huzzey, Zoë Laidlaw, Alison Light, Anita Rupprecht, Verene A. Shepherd, Andrea Stuart and Vijaya Teelock.The impact of slavery and slave-ownership is once again becoming a major area of historical and contemporary concern: this book makes a vital contribution to the subject.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnslaved personsxEmancipationzGreat BritainxHistoryvCongresses. 0aEnslaved personsxEmancipationzWest Indies, BritishxHistoryvCongresses. 0aSlaveholdersxCongressesxHistoryxGreat Britain. 0aSlaveholderszGreat BritainxHistoryvCongresses. 0aSlaveryxColonieszGreat BritainxHistoryvCongresses. 0aSlaveryxCongressesxColoniesxHistoryxGreat Britain. 0aSlaveryxCongressesxEconomic aspectsxGreat Britain. 0aSlaveryxCongressesxHistoryxWest Indies, BritishxWest IndiesxBritish West IndiesxGreat Britain. 0aSlaveryxEconomic aspectszGreat BritainvCongresses. 0aSlaveryzWest Indies, BritishxHistoryvCongresses. 0aSlavesxCongressesxEmancipationxHistoryxGreat Britain. 0aSlavesxCongressesxEmancipationxHistoryxWest Indies, British. 0aSlavesxEmancipationzGreat BritainxHistoryvCongresses. 0aSlavesxEmancipationzWest Indies, BritishxHistoryvCongresses. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBritish Empire.  aCa